I'm still unsure why â€œMingus Ah Umâ€ comes to everyone so highly recommended when this came out just a year later and covers everything that album does much more concisely and interestingly. That album had a lot of tracks which tweedled on and didn't go anywhere particularly interesting - this one recognizes that and contains six tracks, and not one of them doesn't deserve a place on here.
Tracks like â€œWednesday Night Prayer Meetingâ€ and â€œMoanin'â€ are some of the best I've heard from 60s jazz, and they all just present this fantastically chilled out image. It also displays next to none of the avant-garde experimentation which would become his forte, despite what the sub-genres here would have you believe. Normally I'm of the opinion that an album is best when it's experimenting and pushing new boundaries, but honestly I think this album still pushes that boundaries but in the direction of opening up new ideas within post-bop, not tearing it all down and starting over again like his later work suggests.
While Mingus's discography is obviously very intimidating, and I can't pretend I'm anywhere close to hearing it all, this has to be an absolutely essential cornerstone of it
